<HEADLINE>
OVER 9,600 PEOPLE INDICTED FOR CORRUPTION SINCE JULY 2000
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April  29 (CNA) 04/29/07  16:08:41 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The nation's public prosecutors have handled 3,700 corruption
cases and prosecuted more than 9,600 people since the Ministry of
Justice (MOJ) began an operation in July 2000 to crack down on
organized crime and corruption, according to statistics released
by the MOJ Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that during the 81 months from July 2000 to
March 2007, a total of 9,677 suspects involved in 3,731 cases
were prosecuted for benefiting from illegal gains through
corruption and related offenses, and that of this total, 2,043
have been sentenced to various prison terms.
</P>
<P>
The illegal gains involved in cases resulting in a conviction
totaled NT$28.91 billion (US$869.47 million), according to the
MOJ.
</P>
<P>
The 9,677 indicted suspects  include 532 senior government
officials,  583 elected  public  officials,  1,718 middle-level
government officials, 2,892 basic civil servants and 3,952
members of the public.
</P>
<P>
Since July 2000, public prosecutors' offices throughout Taiwan
have dealt with 7,840 cases, representing a decrease of 27.55
percent over the 81-month period from Oct. 1993 to June 2000
prior to the crackdown on organized crime and corruption.
</P>
<P>
The number of prosecuted cases also dropped 6.35 percent to 3,731
from 3,984, while the number of indicted suspects increased 3.61
percent to 9,677.
</P>
